The react sample on error boundaries shows a very simple example, which works, but once you get even a little more detail into it, it will fail.

Say you have this example:
```tsx
const some = null;
return (
    &lt;ErrorBoundary&gt;
        &lt;SomeComponent prop={some.expression.that.fails} /&gt;
    &lt;/ErrorBoundary&gt;
);
```

The defined error-boundary will not catch this error, since the prop is evaluated before the error boundary is.

**Proposed solution:**
So, in order to avoid the above issue (which is easy to overlook, especially for newbies), I wrote the ErrorBoundary class to accept a render prop like this:

```tsx
const RenderComponent = (props: RenderComponentProps) =&gt; props.render();

class ErrorBoundary extends Component&lt;ErrorBoundaryProps, State&gt; {
    static defaultProps = {
        FallbackComponent: GenericError,
    };

    public constructor(props: PropsWithChildren&lt;ErrorBoundaryProps&gt;) {
        super(props);
        this.state = { hasError: false };
    }

    static getDerivedStateFromError(error: Error) {
        return { hasError: true };
    }

    componentDidCatch(error: Error, info: ErrorInfo): void {
        log.error(`Error in component: ${info.componentStack}`, error);
    }

    render() {
        if (this.state.hasError) {
            const { FallbackComponent } = this.props;
            return &lt;FallbackComponent /&gt;;
        }

        return &lt;RenderComponent render={this.props.render} /&gt;;
    }
}
```
Now I can use it like this:
```tsx
const some = null;
return (
    &lt;ErrorBoundary
        render={() =&gt; (
            &lt;SomeComponent prop={some.expression.that.fails} /&gt;
        )}
    /&gt;
);
```
