answers.body_markdown:
&gt; how is it possible to assign a value to undefined? As I understand, undefined is a primitive type in js, then what is the meaning of undefined = true;?  
  
You are right, `undefined` is a primitive type, but it isn&#39;t a [*literal*][1].  
  
When you access `undefined`, you are accessing a property in the global object.  
  
Before ES5, this property was writable, and it could be overridden.  
  
But since ES5, it [was defined as *not writable*](https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/5.1/#sec-15.1.1.3), and now it cannot be changed.  

Not being a literal like [`null`][2], [`true` or `false`][3], makes possible to use `undefined` as a binding name for a variable, a parameter on a function or the name of a function, but not in the global scope. It will clash with the built-in `undefined`.  

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    (function () {
      &#39;use strict&#39;;  
      const undefined = &#39;some value&#39;;  
      console.log(undefined); // &quot;some value&quot;  
    })();
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literal_(computer_programming)
  [2]: https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/10.0/#prod-NullLiteral
  [3]: https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/10.0/#sec-boolean-literals

